amily:Arial; font-size:12pt">subject </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inquiries by the Gwent Police and Crime Panel and your committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Panel acknowledge that the actions taken by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Gwent Police and Crime </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in compliance with the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  However, the Panel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">were not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">convinced that the current legislative framework provides the correct balance between a Commissioners right to remove a Chief Constable (or ask them to retire voluntarily) and a Chief Constable’s ability to demonstrate their suitability to continue (in relation to performance related issues).  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Panel believe that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the first stage of any process to remove or retire a Chief Constable should be undertaken after a prescribed and documented performance assessment has been completed.  This process should be undertaken on a confidential basis and would provide an opportunity for a Commissioner to record performance concerns and give a Chief Constable time to address them or consider their future.  This should be a precursor to any formal or informal process before a Commissioner can remove or retire a Chief Constable.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Turning to the wider role and powers of Police and Crime Panels, the light touch support and challenge expected by the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is not realistic or satisfactory given the wide ranging powers exercised by PCCs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As these new arrangements settle down PCPs are meeting more frequently to ensure they have sufficient capacity to support and hold their PCC to account (Gwent PCP ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">met 8 times since January </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and has another meeting planned before the end of the year). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If real challenge and accountability is to be achieved the role of Panels must be stren</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gthened to ensure that PCPs are consulted before major decisions are taken.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Alternatively, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">if the go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vernment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> content with ‘light touch’ accountability for PCCs then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should acknowledge that the role and effectiveness of PCPs will be limited to a broad overview which will have limited influence.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I hope the above comments assist the Committee’s inquiry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Democratic Service Manager </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Gwent Police and Crime Panel</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>